  <!-- FAQ (kept) -->
  <section class="section" id="Q&A">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">Won't casual Japanese be rude in business settings?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">It's always safe to stay polite in business first. But imagine you're at dinner with colleagues and they start speaking casually to each other. You'll miss the real conversation, the jokes, the bonding. Learning casual Japanese means you can understand when others use it, even if you choose to stay formal.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">What if I make mistakes and offend someone?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">Japanese people are forgiving when they see you're trying to connect genuinely. Making small casual mistakes shows you're human. Staying formal forever often signals distance, not respect.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">Is this just slang and bad grammar?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">No. Casual Japanese follows patterns. It's not “wrong Japanese” — it's the Japanese used daily in real relationships.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">Is this okay if I'm a beginner?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">Yes. Start with a foundation (hiragana + basic listening). Learning casual patterns early prevents you from getting stuck in formal-only mode.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div style="text-align:center;">
